    {
      "id": "l1-perfekt-theory",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "How the Perfekt works",
      "body": "# The perfect tense (Perfekt)\n\nIn spoken German, the **Perfekt** is the normal way to talk about the past. It has **two parts**:\n\n> **haben / sein** (conjugated, position 2) + **past participle** (at the end)\n\n- **Ich habe Pizza gegessen.** — I ate pizza.\n- **Wir sind nach Berlin gefahren.** — We went to Berlin.\n\n## Building the participle\n\n| Type | Pattern | Example |\n|---|---|---|\n| Regular | **ge-** + stem + **-t** | machen → **gemacht** |\n| Irregular | **ge-** + … + **-en** | essen → **gegessen** |\n\n## haben or sein?\n\n- Most verbs use **haben**.\n- Verbs of **movement** or **change of state** use **sein**: *gehen, fahren, kommen, fliegen*.\n\n*Ich bin gegangen* (not *ich habe gegangen*)."
    },
    {
      "id": "l1-ex-match-participles",
      "type": "exercise",
      "theory_ref": "l1-perfekt-theory",
      "title": "Match the participles",
      "exercise": {
        "id": "l1-ex-match-participles",
        "type": "matching",
        "prompt": "Match each German past participle with its English meaning.",
        "card_ids": ["de-a2-gemacht", "de-a2-gekauft", "de-a2-gegessen", "de-a2-getrunken"],
        "pairs": [
          {"left": "gemacht", "right": "done / made"},
          {"left": "gekauft", "right": "bought"},
          {"left": "gegessen", "right": "eaten"},
          {"left": "getrunken", "right": "drunk"}
        ],
        "direction": "target_to_source"
      }
    },
    {
